{
  "text": "In the last decades, numerical models have been developed for the prediction of the propagation of gravity waves in the time domain. These models have been applied to simulated tsunami generation and [CITATION_1] overturning waves [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , to design breakwaters [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] , to predict the wave pressure impact on structures [CITATION_7] , or to study radiation and diffraction waves produced by a wave-maker [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] . Nowadays, because of the increasing interest on the ocean renewable energy, in which the generation systems are installed near-shore or off-shore, new applications of such models are being used to study the fluid-structure interaction considering the effect of the waves [CITATION_12] [CITATION_13] [CITATION_14] [CITATION_15] [CITATION_16] .",
